Let $D$ be the foot of the perpendicular from $I$ to $BC$.  Since $I$ lies on the angle bisector of $\angle B$, we have $BD=CD$.

[asy]
unitsize(0.6inch);
pair A,B,C,D,I;
A=(0,1);
B=(-1,0);
C=(1,0);
I=(0,0);
D=(0,0);
draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(B--I--C);
draw(I--D);
label("$A$",A,N);
label("$B$",B,SW);
label("$C$",C,SE);
label("$D$",D,S);
label("$I$",I,S);
label("$8$",(B+I)/2,W);
[/asy]

Since $\triangle BID$ and $\triangle CID$ are congruent right triangles, we have $ID=ID$ and $BD=CD$.  Furthermore, $BI=CI=8$.

By the Pythagorean Theorem on $\triangle BID$, we have $BD^2+ID^2=8^2=64$.

Since $BD=CD$, the perimeter of $\triangle ABC$ is $AB+AC+BC=2AB+2BD$.

To minimize the perimeter of $\triangle ABC$, we need to minimize $AB+BD$.  By the Triangle Inequality on $\triangle ABI$, we have $AB>AI=8+ID$.  Therefore, $AB+BD>8+ID+BD=8+\sqrt{64-ID^2}$.

Since $ID$ is a positive integer, the smallest possible value of $8+\sqrt{64-ID^2}$ is achieved when $ID=0$, in which case $AB+BD=8+8=16$.

Since $BD=CD$, the smallest possible perimeter of $\triangle ABC$ is $2(AB+BD)=2\cdot 16=\boxed{32}$.

